AB  - Besides liver, IGF-I is expressed in adipose tissue. However, the effects of this local IGF-I on adipose tissue and metabolism are unclear. We generated adipocyte-specific knock-out mice on the background of the Berlin Fat Mouse Inbred (BFMI) line to evaluate the contribution of adipocyte-IGF-I on glucose metabolism and adipose tissue development. BFMI mice are obese, non-diabetic with elevated plasma insulin and IGF-I concentration. The knock-out in adipocytes led to a total white adipose tissue expression of 50-60% due to unaltered Igf-1 expression in stromavascular cells. The lack of IGF-I from adipocytes did not alter plasma IGF-I concentration. BFMI(Chr3)-Igf-I-KO(Q-AT) mice had reduced adipose tissue mass in most depots. During oral glucose tolerance tests, BFMI(Chr3)-Igf-I-KO(Q-AT) mice showed an impaired glucose clearance (p = .03). Interestingly, insulin action was enhanced during insulin tolerance tests (p = .05). In conclusion, adipocyte-specific IGF-I ablation in obese BFMI mice results in reduced adipose tissue mass and thereby alters glucose metabolism.
