AB  - A series of deazaxanthine-based derivatives were rationally prepared and evaluated. 8g exhibited the most potent glucose-lowering effect on HepG2 cell line and modulated adiponectin and leptin expression in 3T3-L1 adipocytes. Oral administration of 8g at 25 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks manifested therapeutic effects on high-fat diet-induced non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) by decreasing the weights of the body, liver, and fat. 8g also modulated the serum levels of fasting glucose and adiponectin, triglycerides, low-density lipoprotein-cholesterol, and alanine aminotransferase, as well as the hepatic concentrations of triglycerides, total cholesterol. Moreover, 8g significantly decreased steatosis and blocked the increase of adipocytes and the size of adipose tissues from NAFLD. In the DIO mice model, 8g ameliorated the obesity-related symptoms and normalized serum biomarkers.
