AB  - This study investigates the metabolic benefits of bacterial cellulose (BC), inulin, and their mixture in high-fat diet (HFD)-fed mice, focusing on their effects on obesity, glucose tolerance, lipid metabolism, and gut microbiota composition. Both BC and inulin effectively suppressed weight gain and fat accumulation, improved glucose tolerance, and reduced plasma cholesterol levels. The mixture group showed an intermediate outcome. Distinct effects on gut microbiota were observed, with BC increasing the abundance of Bifidobacterium, Enterococcus, and Muribaculaceae, contributing to metabolic regulation. However, no significant increase in short-chain fatty acid (SCFA) production was observed in the BC group compared to the cellulose group. Inulin enhanced Lactobacillus, Limosilactobacillus, and Abyssivirga, fostering a prebiotic environment that promoted SCFA production, known for its anti-inflammatory and gut barrier-strengthening properties. These microbiota shifts were closely associated with the metabolic improvements observed. BC’s bile acid-binding capacity enhances bile acid excretion, which supports lipid metabolism and facilitates cholesterol conversion. In contrast, inulin stimulated SCFA production, particularly acetic, propionic, and butyric acids, through its modulation of gut microbiota. These SCFAs support lipid metabolism and improve gut barrier integrity. Together, these fibers demonstrate distinct yet complementary mechanisms: BC primarily acts through bile acid metabolism, enhancing excretion and promoting cholesterol utilization, while inulin exerts its effects by fostering SCFA production and modulating gut microbiota to support systemic metabolic health.
